BT||HT|b|va|4|cs|1|cp|4|fp|3|at|^-{    Responding to Partner's Splinter bid    }
^-|CP||FP||at|^B@2^Z@3The worst holdings opposite partner's splinter bid are strength and shortness. K-Q doubleton in your hand opposite partner's singleton is one loser - just as if you had no honors in the suit at all. Because partner has length in the other suits, you are not likely to get a useful discard from his hand on the other honor once opponents take their Ace.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

Further, when partner splinters, a doubleton is not the asset you thought it would be. You were hoping that having only two cards in the suit would allow you to ruff partner's loser(s). Partner had such high hopes for his singleton that he upgraded it to 3 dummy points. Unfortunately, neither short suit will generate any extra winners.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


at|

While your holding in partner's short suit is relevant, don't forget to look at the rest of your hand. On a distributional hand, extra trumps are worth their weight in gold. Although a 9 - card fit and a singleton is nice.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


at|

There are plenty of unsuccessful slams where a 10th trump would have made all the difference in the world. If opener shows a short suit after a Jacoby 2NT response, it is the equivalent of a splinter bid, so the above guidelines are equally relevant.|
